<h1>Comparison</h1>
<br>
<h2>The Motivations</h2>
<br>
<p>
For the U.S., the main motivation for high school CS education is industrial demands. For China, the main motivation is to prepare students to be qualified citizens of the information age. Due to different motivations, the two countries have different practitioners in CS education. Because China has strong precollege math and science education, and there is little talk about “the STEM worker shortage”, thus unlike the U.S., industry does not play a substantial role in Chinese CS education. Also, there are few, if any, Chinese non-profits seeking to popularize CS knowledge, probably because all schools are required to incorporate the IT curriculum already.
</p>
<h2 class = "readMore" id = "readMore1">Read More &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp<img class="downArrow" src = '/images/arrows.png'/></h2>
<div class = "moreText" id = "text1">
<p>
However, these two motivations are not totally unrelated. In his weekly address promoting the CS for All initiative, President Obama proclaimed, “they [the young people] are the ones to ensure America, the country that invented this stuff [CS] in the first place, keeps growing, keeps innovating, and keeps leading the world in the years ahead.” <a href="/bib/?entry=obama">(Obama 2016)</a> By pointing out that CS originated in the U.S., Obama is appealing to a strong sense of national pride—the pride of being a U.S. citizen. On the other hand, in China the IT curriculum is seen as part of quality-oriented education, and an important aim of quality-oriented education is to improve the overall quality of the future workforce. This aim, too, is driven by industrial demands.
</p>
</div>
