<br>
<h2>Uneven Distribution of Resources</h2>
<br>
<p>
For both countries, resources for high quality education are very limited. Worse, the scarce resources are distributed highly unevenly. Traditionally more privileged groups are more likely to get access to CS education in high school. In the U.S., middle and higher class white and Asian males are more likely to get access. In China, although the IT curriculum is implemented by every high school, richer high schools are more likely to offer more challenging electives (e.g. Introduction to Artificial Intelligence), CNOI trainings, and even AP CS. Males are also more likely to major in CS than females. The uneven distribution of resources has historical roots: in the U.S., people with higher socioeconomic power are more likely to be white males due to historic reasons, and in China, the society has long been patriarchal.
</p>
<h2 class = "readMore" id = "readMore2">Read More &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp<img class="downArrow" src = '/images/arrows.png'/></h2>
<div class = "moreText" id = "text2">
<p>
Yet there is no naturally, or genetically, existing relationships among race, gender, and computer science. Articulations play a large part in forming and reinforcing the stereotypes of CS. For instance, in the U.S., when personal computers first entered market, many were advertised as toys for young boys. In movies and TV shows too, white and Asian males were far more likely to do computer science than any other group <a href="/bib/?entry=google2015">(Google 2015)</a>. When media portrayals frequently associate CS with certain race and gender groups, more marginalized groups like females and URMs may feel discourage to pursue CS.
</p>
<p><img src="images/gwc.jpg" alt="Girls Who Code" id = "img1"/></p>
<p class = "caption"><a href = "http://money.cnn.com/2016/01/19/technology/girls-who-code-1-million-in-scholarships/" target="_blank">Non-profits Like Girls Who Code Trying to Close the Gender Gap</a></p>
<p>
One of the most prominent inequalities in CS education in both countries is the gender gap. In the U.S., according to a research by <a href="https://girlswhocode.com" target="_blank">Girls Who Code</a> and Accenture, the largest drop off of percentages of girls interested in CS happen in high school <a href="/bib/?entry=accenture">(Accenture & Girls Who Code 2016)</a>. While various factors may be at play in forming the “high school trap”, from developmental psychology’s point of view, in high schools teenagers are more aware of their sexual development, and they are very susceptible to peer pressure. Thus if females do not see their friends choosing CS courses, they are less likely to do so as well <a href="/bib/?entry=google2015">(Google 2015)</a>. On the other hand, in China students usually do not have the freedom to choose individual courses: they can only choose tracks. Thus if everyone is required to take the same courses, females may feel less awkward in taking CS courses. Yet notably, while the gender gap still clearly exists in China, there are very few researches on this topic, so it remains unclear what factors contributed to the gender gap.
</p>
<p>
Realizing these problems, efforts are on the way to make changes. Especially in the U.S., various organizations are trying to disarticulate the strong associations between CS and certain demographic groups, and to rearticulate CS as something for everyone. Developing culturally relevant curricula and creating inclusive classroom environments, too, can be vital. Indeed, if high school females see “students like me” engaged in CS, they are more likely to be interested as well <a href="/bib/?entry=google2015">(Google 2015)</a>.
</p>
</div>
