<br>
<h2>The International Trend: CS for Everyone</h2>
<br>
<p>
Regardless of motivations, education practitioners in both countries think that CS should be for everyone: it is no longer enough to simply teach students how to use software, which is the current case with many computer classes in both countries. Instead, students should be creators of software and drive future innovations. “As we see it, digital fluency requires not just the ability to chat, browse, and interact but also the ability to design, create, and invent with new media,” <a href="/bib/?entry=resnick">(Resnick et al. 2009)</a> said the <a href="https://scratch.mit.edu" target="_blank">Scratch</a> developers. Many support this view, and following this view, both countries have identified problems in their high school CS education. In the U.S., researchers have found that “states are focused almost exclusively on skill-based aspects of computing (such as, using a computer in other learning activities) and have few standards on the conceptual aspects of computer science that lay the foundation for innovation and deeper study in the field.” <a href="/bib/?entry=acm">(ACM & CSTA 2010)</a> In China, researchers have pointed out that most of the IT curriculum simply teaches students how to use various software applications <a href="/bib/?entry=zhu">(Zhu & Li 2005)</a>, and that the electives which do incorporate significant CS knowledge to empower students to be creators (e.g. Algorithm and Program Design) are being offered a lot less often <a href="/bib/?entry=xiao2014">(Xiao, Guo, Fan & Huang 2014)</a>.
</p>
<h2 class = "readMore" id = "readMore3">Read More &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp<img class="downArrow" src = '/images/arrows.png'/></h2>
<div class = "moreText" id = "text3">
<p><img src="images/scratch.jpg" alt="Scratch" width="300"/></p>
<p class = "caption"><a href = "https://cacm.acm.org/magazines/2009/11/48421-scratch-programming-for-all/fulltext" target="_blank">Scratch Trying to Foster Creativity and Make Programming for All</a></p>
<p>
In light of the need for CS for everyone, in both countries school is the most important channel for high school CS education. In the U.S., although industry and non-profits offer various programs, the high schools still have the ability to reach out to the most amount of students. In China, almost all efforts of CS education are linked to high schools. In order for more high schools to provide CS education, policies on graduation requirements play an important role in both countries, and assessment criteria plays an important role in establishing policies on graduation requirements: knowing how to assess CS makes it easier for schools to count CS as part of graduation requirement, and consequently to allocate more resources to CS. Yet CS education has faced tensions with assessments in both countries. Especially in China, while knowing the importance of assessments, educators struggle hard not to make the IT curriculum another exam-oriented curriculum.
</p>
<p>
Along with assessment criteria, graduation requirement, and other factors, articulation is also important in advocating CS education. In order for more people to realize the importance of CS education, various efforts have been made to articulate high school CS course as a rigorous academic discipline of fundamental importance, rather than as optional technical or vocational training. Some influential organizations such as ACM and CSTA tried to articulate different definitions of “computer science” and “technology literacy and fluency”, giving a more rigorous definition to the former <a href="/bib/?entry=acm">(ACM & CSTA 2010)</a>. A lot of practitioners also looked at the articulation of computational thinking as a way to elevate the status of CS education, for Wing claims that computational thinking should be as fundamental in education as reading, writing, and arithmetic <a href="/bib/?entry=wing">(Wing 2006)</a>. Computational thinking has evoked popular responses internationally: many U.S. curriculums, including AP CS Principles, now adapt principles of computational thinking, and Wing’s original three-page article has been translated into Chinese as well.
</p>
<p>
However, there are some that articulate against overstressing the importance of computational thinking, or STEM in general. Some argue that computation cannot fundamentally transform human societies, and the rigid and orderly ways computer programs work may not be the way complex human societies work <a href="/bib/?entry=golumbia">(Golumbia 2009)</a>. Thus, it is doubtful whether computational thinking is as fundamental as its supporters claim to be, and whether it is as useful in daily lives. Moreover, in trying to get more students interested in CS, many paint rosy pictures of technology by saying that “CS is changing the world”, or “technology empowers people”, or “technology does social good”, etc. While technology may indeed change some people’s lives for the better, these rosy pictures often ignore the negative sides of technology, which are worthy to keep in mind as well. Thus, while CS education and computational thinking are important, stressing those should not come at the expense of further marginalizing some other disciplines with less emphasis devoted to, usually humanities and the arts.
</p>
